folk, Massachusetts, Amerikas Forenede Stater","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"7 August 1575–1633":"7 augustus 1575–1633","1596–Female":"1596–Overleden","1603–1637":"1603–1637","–1670":"–1670","–Male":"Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1575–1633":"1575–1633","1633":"1633","1575":"1575","1596":"1596","July 1603":"juli 1603","1670":"1670","7 August 1575":"7 augustus 1575","1637":"1637","1603":"1603","London, Greater London, England":"Blendon, London, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Boston, Suffolk, Massachusetts, United States":"Boston, Suffolk, Massachusetts, Verenigde Staten van Amerika","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"7 August 1575–1633":"7 August 1575–1633","1596–Female":"1596–Deceased","1603–1637":"1603–1637","–1670":"–1670","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1575–1633":"1575–1633","1633":"1633","1575":"1575","1596":"1596","July 1603":"July 1603","1670":"1670","7 August 1575":"7 August 1575","1637":"1637","1603":"1603","London, Greater London, England":"Blendon, London, England, United Kingdom","Boston, Suffolk, Massachusetts, United States":"Boston, Suffolk, Massachusetts, United States","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Adams","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Dutch, and German (mainly northwestern Germany): patronymic from the personal name   Adam  . In North America, this surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. Greek   Adamopoulos  , Serbian and Croatian <b>Adamović</b> (see   Adamovich  ), Polish (and Jewish)   Adamski  .","Irish and Scottish: adopted for   McAdam   or a Scottish variant of   Adam  , with excrescent <i>-s</i>.","History: This surname was borne by two early presidents of the US, father and son. They were descended from Henry Adams, who settled in Braintree, MA, in 1635/6, from Barton St. David, Somerset, England. The younger of them, John Quincy Adams (1767–1848) derived his middle name from his maternal grandmother's surname (see   Quincy  ). — Another important New England family, established mainly in NH, is descended from William Adams, who emigrated from Shropshire, England, to Dedham, MA, in 1628. James Hopkins Adams (1812–61), governor of SC, was unconnected with either of these families, his ancestry being Welsh; his forebears entered North America through PA."],"variants":[{"name":"Adam","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Vito, Angelo, Antonio, Salvatore, Giuseppe, Santo, Giovanna, Nicola, Aldo, Baldassare, Carmelo, Carmino.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Adamo</i>, the Italian form of   Adam  ."]},{"name":"Addams","meanings":["English: variant of   Adams  ."]}]},{"name":"Jacob","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, from Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>. This was borne by perhaps the most important of all the patriarchs in the Book of Genesis. Jacob was the father of twelve sons, who gave their names to the twelve tribes of Israel. He was the son of Isaac and Rebecca and twin brother of Esau. According to the story in Genesis, he was the cunning younger twin, who persuaded his brother Esau to part with his right to his inheritance in exchange for a bowl of soup (‘a mess of pottage’). Later, he tricked his blind and dying father into blessing him in place of Esau. The derivation of the name has been much discussed. It is traditionally explained as being derived from Hebrew <i>akev</i> ‘heel’ and to have meant ‘heel grabber’, because when Jacob was born ‘his hand took hold of Esau's heel’ (Genesis 25:26). This is interpreted later in the Bible as ‘supplanter’ Esau himself remarks, ‘Is he not rightly named Jacob? for he has supplanted me these two times’ (Genesis 27:36). <i>Jacob</i> is especially common as a Jewish given name, although it also became very popular among the Puritans from the 16th century onwards, and has again been widely used since the 1990s.  Compare  James ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Jacob Adams was born on 7 August 1575, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 2 sons and 3 daughters with Mary Adams. He died in 1633, in Boston, Suffolk, Massachusetts, United States, at the age of 58."},"et":{"7 August 1575–1633":"7. august 1575–1633","1596–Female":"1596–Surnud","1603–1637":"1603–1637","–1670":"–1670","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1575–1633":"1575–1633","1633":"1633","1575":"1575","1596":"1596","July 1603":"juuli 1603","1670":"1670","7 August 1575":"7. august 1575","1637":"1637","1603":"1603","London, Greater London, England":"Blendon, London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Boston, Suffolk, Massachusetts, United States":"Boston, Suffolk, Massachusetts, Ameerika Ühendriigid","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"7 August 1575–1633":"7. elokuuta 1575–1633","1596–Female":"1596–Kuollut","1603–1637":"1603–1637","–1670":"–1670","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1575–1633":"1575–1633","1633":"1633","1575":"1575","1596":"1596","July 1603":"heinäkuu 1603","1670":"1670","7 August 1575":"7. elokuuta 1575","1637":"1637","1603":"1603","London, Greater London, England":"Blendon, London, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Boston, Suffolk, Massachusetts, United States":"Boston, Suffolk, Massachusetts, Yhdysvallat","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"7 August 1575–1633":"7 août 1575–1633","1596–Female":"1596–Décédée","1603–1637":"1603–1637","–1670":"–1670","–Male":"Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1575–1633":"1575–1633","1633":"1633","1575":"1575","1596":"1596","July 1603":"juillet 1603","1670":"1670","7 August 1575":"7 août 1575","1637":"1637","1603":"1603","London, Greater London, England":"Blendon, Londres, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Boston, Suffolk, Massa